{
  "explanation": "The key difference between an American option and a European option lies in their exercise terms. A European option can only be exercised on its expiration date, while an American option can be exercised at any point up to and including the expiration date. This means the holder of an American option possesses all the rights of a European option holder (specifically, the right to exercise at expiration) plus the additional right to exercise early. In financial theory, additional rights or flexibility can never detract from value; they can only add value or have neutral value. This 'early exercise privilege' is a feature that the European option lacks. Because the American option provides the holder with a superset of the rights available to the European option holder, its price must be at least as high. The additional rights are the direct source of this value relationship."
}
